<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="498" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,325,452]" pageId="1" pageNumber="498">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,268,325,348]" pageId="1" pageNumber="498">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The male imago of 
<taxonomicName box="[481,743,325,348]" class="Insecta" family="Leptohyphidae" genus="Macunahyphes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="498" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eduardoi">
<emphasis box="[481,743,325,348]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="498">Macunahyphes eduardoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp nov. can be distinguished from all congeners by the following combination of characteristics: 
<number box="[504,516,360,383]" pageId="1" pageNumber="498" value="1.0">1</number>
) Forewing translucent with costal and subcostal area tinged with grey and with longitudinal vein CuP absent (
<figureCitation box="[484,577,394,417]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 4" captionStartId="1.[151,258,1982,2004]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,496,1970]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[151,1436,496,1970]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 4. Macunahyphes eduardoi sp. nov. (Ephemeroptera, Leptohyphidae). Male imago. Figure 1. Forewing. Figure 2. Detail of elongated projections of penes (ventral view). Figure 3. Habitus (dorsal view, scale 1 mm). Figure 4. Genitalia (ventral view)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/235209/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="498">
Figure 
<number box="[565,577,394,417]" pageId="1" pageNumber="498" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
); 
<number box="[604,618,394,417]" pageId="1" pageNumber="498" value="2.0">2</number>
) penes wide (
<figureCitation box="[773,870,394,417]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 4" captionStartId="1.[151,258,1982,2004]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,496,1970]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[151,1436,496,1970]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 4. Macunahyphes eduardoi sp. nov. (Ephemeroptera, Leptohyphidae). Male imago. Figure 1. Forewing. Figure 2. Detail of elongated projections of penes (ventral view). Figure 3. Habitus (dorsal view, scale 1 mm). Figure 4. Genitalia (ventral view)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/235209/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="498">
Figure 
<number box="[854,870,394,417]" pageId="1" pageNumber="498" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
); 
<number box="[893,906,394,417]" pageId="1" pageNumber="498" value="3.0">3</number>
) penes lobes with pair of elongated spines with small lateral hook-shaped projections from the base to the middle region. (
<figureCitation box="[944,1038,429,452]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 4" captionStartId="1.[151,258,1982,2004]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,496,1970]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[151,1436,496,1970]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 4. Macunahyphes eduardoi sp. nov. (Ephemeroptera, Leptohyphidae). Male imago. Figure 1. Forewing. Figure 2. Detail of elongated projections of penes (ventral view). Figure 3. Habitus (dorsal view, scale 1 mm). Figure 4. Genitalia (ventral view)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/235209/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="498">
Figure 
<number box="[1022,1038,429,452]" pageId="1" pageNumber="498" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
